<p class=""><h2>Key Challenges in the Rubber-Tyred Metros Market</h2><ul>    <li><strong>Infrastructure Limitations:</strong> The development of rubber-tyred metro systems requires significant investment in infrastructure, including dedicated tracks, stations, and maintenance facilities. Existing transport frameworks may need extensive upgrades to accommodate such systems.</li>    <li><strong>Operational Efficiency:</strong> Maintaining operational efficiency in rubber-tyred metros can be challenging due to factors like wear and tear from rubber wheels, tire replacement costs, and the need for specialized maintenance protocols.</li>    <li><strong>Regulatory Hurdles:</strong> Navigating the complex regulatory landscape can pose barriers to entry. Compliance with safety standards, environmental regulations, and local government policies varies across regions and can slow project implementation.</li>    <li><strong>Market Competition:</strong> The market faces stiff competition from established rail systems and other forms of public transport. Convincing stakeholders of the benefits of rubber-tyred metros over traditional rail systems may present a significant challenge.</li>    <li><strong>Funding and Investment Scarcity:</strong> Securing funding for innovative projects can be difficult due to the high capital expenditures required upfront. Economic downturns can exacerbate funding challenges, limiting the growth potential of new metro lines.</li></ul><h2>Potential Growth Opportunities in the Rubber-Tyred Metros Market</h2><ul>    <li><strong>Technological Innovation:</strong> Advances in technology, such as real-time data analytics, automated systems, and energy-efficient designs, present opportunities to enhance operational efficiency and improve passenger experience in rubber-tyred metros.</li>    <li><strong>Urbanization Trends:</strong> As urban populations grow, the demand for efficient and flexible public transportation solutions rises. Rubber-tyred metros of